  "title": "Even when prototypes tackle public issues, such as the measurement of pollution or the search for green energy, they rarely have a well-measured impact on science or society at large.",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "paragraph": "The contradictions in the effects of prototyping are what we claim saves politics and agency from the rule of Chronos and teleology of Instauratio. We need experimental and participatory practices to democratize the future and bridge various divides that will support curiosity and dreams against automation with its visions of total control over time and the future. ",
      "summary": "The impact of prototyping is contradictory and this paradox is what helps maintain political and personal agency. The text advocates for experimental and participatory methods to democratize future-making and counteract automation's total control over time and the future.",
      "questions": [
        "What is the role of prototyping in maintaining political and personal agency?",
        "Why do we need experimental and participatory methodologies?",
        "How can we counteract automation's total control over time and the future?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "paragraph": "Demarcating Science and Technology from Society\n\n\n Laboratory studies and the history of scientific show that all science instruments are deeply embedded in the social, political, and religious processes of society that are often controversial and ambiguous. In this sense, the emancipatory and exploratory uses of the OSH prototypes make this process visible and accessible to the public.",
      "summary": "Scientific instruments are deeply rooted in societal processes, including social, political, and religious ones. The use of Open Source Hardware (OSH) prototypes makes the intertwining of these areas apparent and accessible to the public.",
      "questions": [
        "How are scientific instruments embedded in societal processes?",
        "In what ways are these relationships controversial and ambiguous?",
        "How do OSH prototypes make this interconnection visible and accessible to the public?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "paragraph": "The complex history of political, artistic, economic and other (mis)uses of prototypes is well documented in the famous studies of Robert Boyle's air pump (Schaffer, 1987; Shapin & Schaffer, 2011), Samuel Morland's calculating machines (Ratcliff, 2007), Rene Descartes's garden machinery and automata fountain (Werrett, 2001), Cornelius Debbel's incubators and thermostates (Keller, 2010, 2013), and various aesthetic, metaphysical, poetic and other uses of instruments in alchemy and mechanical arts (Keller, 2013; Newman, 2005; Nummedal, 2011). ",
      "summary": "The use of prototypes has a complex history spanning political, artistic, and economic realms, as evidenced by various studies on famous inventions such as Boyle's air pump, Morland's calculating machines, Descartes's garden machinery, and Debbel's incubators.",
      "questions": [
        "What is the history of the use of prototypes in different sectors?",
        "How have famous inventions like Boyle's air pump and Morland's calculating machines used prototypes?",
        "What are some of the various uses of prototypes in alchemy and mechanical arts?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "paragraph": "Simon Schaffer (1987) showed how the new experimental and epistemic practices and methods in the case of the air pump helped to preserve the theological themes of spirits and souls. The air pump even created a new discipline dedicated to the agenda of pneumatics and pneumatology as a study of these spirits. Francis Bacon, as Robert Boyle, but also Robert Hook and later even Isaac Newton, perceived their roles more as ‘priests of nature’ than men of science, and believed that science must be pious by proving the authority of divine power and plan (Ibid..). In the Section on Francis Bacon (2.3 and 2.4), we will explain how this led to the teleological and theological agenda of Instauratio advocating science and technology that support the rule of patrons and God over the future. ",
      "summary": "The new practices and methods in the case of the air pump helped to preserve theological themes. This led to a new discipline centered around the study of spirits, pneumatics, and pneumatology. Prominent figures like Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, and Isaac Newton saw their roles more as 'priests of nature' than as scientists, advocating for a science that proves the authority of divine power.",
      "questions": [
        "How did the air pump help preserve theological themes?",
        "What is the role of religion in the views of Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, and Isaac Newton?",
        "How did this lead to the teleological and theological agenda of Instauratio?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "paragraph": "The revival of instrument making in the hackerspaces and makerspaces challenges the idea of public defined by Joseph Wright’s classic 18th century painting ‘An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump.’ The painting shows laboratory equipment that provides data to the scientists, but also forms the public opinion and response to science (Baudot, 2012; van Helden, 1991). On the painting, a scientist, supposedly Robert Boyle, performs the new instrument suffocating a bird in the vacuum in front of a lay audience that includes women and children. The terrifying and visceral experience not only reveals the hidden forces in nature but also forms the public opinion of science through fear and awe.",
      "summary": "The resurgence of instrument making in hackerspaces and makerspaces challenges traditional perceptions of the public, as illustrated by Joseph Wright’s 18th-century painting 'An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump.' The painting not only demonstrates how scientific instruments provide data, but also how they shape public opinion and reactions to science.",
